To determine the angular magnification of a telescope, we will use the formula:

\[ M = \frac{f_{\text{objective}}}{f_{\text{eye-piece}}} + 1 \]

Where:
\( f_{\text{objective}} \) = focal length of the objective lens
\( f_{\text{eye-piece}} \) = focal length of the eye-piece lens

Given:
\( f_{\text{eye-piece}} = 20 \, \text{cm} \)
\( f_{\text{objective}} = -100 \, \text{cm} \) (since the objective lens is converging)

Plugging in the values:

\[ M = \frac{-100}{20} + 1 = -5 + 1 = -4 \]

The angular magnification of the telescope is 4. Therefore, the correct answer is:

H: 4.
